es of cultural creativity that connected to larger debates in the widening field of the maritime humanities. For Blackmore, the sea, ships, and nautical travel unfold into a variety of symbolic dimensions, and the oceans across the globe that were traversed in the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries correspond to vast reaches within the literary self. The sea and seafaring were not merely themes in textual culture but were also principles that created individual and collective subjects according to oceanic modes of perception. Blackmore concludes with a discussion of depth and sinking in shipwreck narratives as metaphoric and discursive dimensions of the maritime subject, foreshadowing empire’s decline.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPortuguese literatureyClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aSea in literature. 0aSeafaring life in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aPortugal, Iberia, sea, seafaring, Luís de Camões, maritime humanities, early modern, maritime empire, ships, literary culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107665090 cprintz978022682046040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226820477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226820477/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022